  "text": "Let ϕ, ψ ∈ N and n ≥ 2. A sequence (z 1 , . . . , z n ) of points in R d is called a descending chain in (ϕ, ψ) if z i ∈ ϕ for odd i ∈ {1, . . . , n}, z i ∈ ψ for even i ∈ {1, . . . , n} and z i prefers z i+1 to z i−1 for each i ∈ {2, . . . , n − 1}. Note that any pair (z 1 , z 2 ) ∈ ϕ × ψ is a descending chain. An infinite sequence (z 1 , z 2 , . . .) of points in R d is called an infinite descending chain if for every n ≥ 2, (z 1 , . . . , z n ) is a descending chain. The following result can be proved as Lemma 15 in [CITATION_1] . Lemma 2.2. Let ϕ, ψ ∈ N, and suppose that there is no infinite descending chain in (ϕ, ψ). Then ϕ ∞ = ∅ or ψ ∞ = ∅, and there is a unique stable partial matching from ϕ to ψ, which is produced by the mutual nearest neighbor matching. Remark 2.3. In d = 1, there is no infinite descending chain in (Z, ψ) for any ψ ∈ N. Otherwise there would be an infinite descending chain in Z. The corresponding statement does not hold for any d > 1. For later use we define the the matching status of a point as the (measurable) function",
